05310nam a22007935i 9780292754645DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212014txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927546457 a10.7560/7546382doi  a(DE-B1597)586978  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGN21.L797 -- A66 2014eb 7aPHO0110302bisacsh04a305.8002221 aBroyles, Bill, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmong Unknown Tribes :bRediscovering the Photographs of Explorer Carl Lumholtz /cAnn Christine Eek, Bill Broyles, Phyllis La Farge, Richard Laugharn, Eugenia Macías Guzmán. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tTimeline -- t1 Carl Lumholtz and His Photographs -- tFolio One -- t2 Looking for Lumholtz -- t3 What Photographs Can Tell Us -- tFolio Two -- t4 New Trails and Entwined Legacies -- t5 A Man of Qualities -- tReflections -- tNotes for the Photographic Plates -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex of Plates -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInternationally renowned as an exciting guide to unknown peoples and places, Norwegian Carl Lumholtz was a Victorian-era explorer, anthropologist, natural scientist, writer, and photographer who worked in Australia, Mexico, and Borneo. His photographs of the Tarahumara, Huichol, Cora, Tepehuan, Southern Pima, and Tohono O’odham tribes of Mexico and southwest Arizona were among the very first taken of these cultures and still provide the best photographic record of them at the turn of the twentieth century. Lumholtz published his photographs in several books, including Unknown Mexico and New Trails in Mexico, but, because photographic publishing was then in its infancy, most of the images were poorly printed, badly cropped, or reworked by “illustrators” using crude techniques. Among Unknown Tribes presents more than two hundred of Lumholtz’s best photographs—many never before published—from the archives of the American Museum of Natural History in New York and the Museum of Cultural History in Oslo, Norway. The images are newly scanned, most from the original negatives, and printed uncropped, disclosing a wealth of previously hidden detail. Each photograph is fully identified and often amplified by Lumholtz’s own notes and captions. Accompanying the images are essays and photo notes that survey Lumholtz’s career and legacy, as well as what his photographs reveal about the “unknown tribes.” By giving Lumholtz’s photographs the high-quality reproduction they deserve, Among Unknown Tribes honors not only the Norwegian explorer but also the native peoples who continue to struggle for recognition and justice as they actively engage in the traditional customs that Lumholtz recorded.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aEthnologistszGermanyvBiography. 0aEthnologyvPictorial works. 0aExplorerszGermanyvBiography. 0aNaturalistszGermanyvBiography. 0aPhotography in ethnology. 7aPhotography / Individual Photographers / Monographs.2bisacsh1 aBroyles, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEek, Ann Christine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aEek, Ann Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuzmán, Eugenia Macías, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGuzmán, Eugenia Macías, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLa Farge, Phyllis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLa Farge, Phyllis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular